    value: 옛날에 공자(孔子)의 제자 자로(子路)가 젊어서 집이 가난하였는데 백 리나 되는 곳에 가서 쌀을 져다가 부모를 봉양하였다고 한다.
english:
  title: Record of the Shrine of Lord Jeong, Duke of Korea
  author: Lee Gok
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The practice of building shrines and conducting ancestral rites is ancient. Those who serve their parents build shrines in their homes; for the sage, the virtuous, and those of great merit, shrines are erected in the state or district. Such customs can be traced through history. Since the Han Dynasty, ritual practice has evolved with the times. Some have replaced the spirit tablet with a portrait in the shrine; others have abandoned regular offerings in pursuit of blessings. Thus, beyond the family shrine, there arose the memorial hall. Yet the heart that repays one's parents and honors distant ancestors remains one.

    Because merit and virtue vary in magnitude, so too does the repayment—some generous, some meager—and the duration of offerings likewise differs. When the late Magistrate Jeong decided to build a shrine for his parents, he spoke to me, a fellow villager surnamed Lee, saying: "In my youth, I left my parents' side; now I am old, and they have long since departed this world. How can I ever fully express my gratitude or ease the sorrow of my separation from them? Yet, through the grace of Heaven, this unworthy body has been elevated to serve in the imperial court. My rank is high, my stipend generous, and my ancestors three generations have been honored with posthumous titles, their spirits blessed in the nine springs below. I wish to build a hall beside the Buddhist temple, to place their likenesses there, to make offerings for their welfare, and to ensure their worship endures. Let the imperial edicts of our enlightened rulers be carved in stone and set beneath the eaves, so that I might display the sovereign's favor and find solace in my filial devotion. I ask you to compose an inscription for me." Thus was the Shrine of the Duke of Korea conceived, and thus this record comes to be written.

    According to the Rites: "When the father is a gentleman and the son a great official, the burial follows the rites of a gentleman, but the sacrifices follow those of a great official." Humbly I consider that our sage dynasty, through its benevolence, embraces all under heaven, and through filial piety governs the world, thereby nurturing the hearts of its people and elevating their spirit. All officials, both civil and military, from the rank of purple robes upward, are permitted to honor their parents with posthumous rank. The degrees multiply, the honors abound. Only those whose households lack proper ritual vessels or whose conduct is deficient are excluded—and this applies even to one's parents and wife. Alas! In bestowing such grace while also demanding virtue, does not the sage ruler embody the unity of moral teaching and ritual propriety, the simultaneous work of reward and admonition without contradiction?

    Moreover, I have observed that accumulated virtue and accumulated vice bring corresponding fortune and calamity. When not visited upon oneself, they inevitably fall upon one's descendants. Some inherit family wealth and hereditary position, basking in imperial favor, commanding a thousand mounted guards in procession, spending ten thousand coins on a single meal—until disaster strikes and ruin extends to their heirs. Others rise from humble hovels to heights of honor, their names inscribed in history, their filial devotion reaching even the spirits. Examining the causes, these outcomes are no mere chance.

    Now consider the ancestors of the Duke of Korea. Though their merit and virtue were not known in their time, they have borne a son of such eminence that he enjoys rewards as magnificent as these. Is this not the fruit of their accumulated goodness? How much more so when the Magistrate himself, having studied the writings of the ancients, walks the path of a true man—governing himself by integrity, conducting affairs with impartiality, serving the throne with humble devotion while rising above the common gentry, and through his achievement bringing honor to his parents. Is this not praiseworthy?

    The Duke of Korea was named Jen, of the Jeong clan, a native of Hadong in Goryeo. He received the posthumous rank of Grand Commandant of Glorious Repute, Minister of the Secretariat in Liaodong and other regions, and was posthumously enfeoffed as Duke of Korea. His father, named Seongryang, received the posthumous rank of Minister of the Left, Secretariat of the Provinces, and was posthumously enfeoffed as Duke of Yongyang. His mother, Lady Pao, was posthumously enfeoffed as Duchess of Yongyang. His grandfather, named Gongyun, received the posthumous rank of Counselor of the Secretariat in the Northern Territories and was posthumously enfeoffed as Duke of Yongyang. His grandmother, Lady Choi, was posthumously enfeoffed as Duchess of Yongyang. His wife, Lady Lee, was enfeoffed as Great Duchess of Korea. He had five sons: the eldest, Yunhwa, rose to Magistrate; the second, Yungi, rose to Commander; the third, Dumandar, was the Magistrate himself; the fourth, Bujwa, rose to Judge of the Inner Ministry; the fifth, whose name I omit, did not serve. He had three daughters and several grandchildren.

    In the year Genzi of the Dade era, when the Magistrate was but eleven years old, he entered service as an attendant to King Chungryeol on a mission to the imperial court, where he remained to serve at the palace. Emperor Chengzong, admiring his brilliance and keen intelligence, decreed in the year Renyin that he be admitted to the Imperial Academy to study alongside the sons of nobility. Having grasped the essential principles of ritual and letters, he was appointed to serve in the household of the future Emperor Renzong. In the year Jiyou of the Zhidaye era, he was made Assistant Director of the Imperial Treasuries with the rank of Instructor of the Palace. Soon he was promoted to Director of Ceremonial Vessels, and thereafter rose through six promotions to the rank of Emissary, receiving the title of Grand Commandant. He became Acting Director of the Bureau of Imperial Regalia and Jade, overseeing the precious treasures. Among those held in favor by Emperor Renzong, none surpassed him. In the early years of the Tianli era, he became Keeper of the Imperial Insignia, and later resumed his post as Director of Ceremonial Vessels. He subsequently advanced four more times to become Grand Commandant, Magistrate, and Keeper of Rites, then Supervisor of Court Audiences. During his tenure as Magistrate, he made it his personal mission to recommend capable and virtuous men, and the scholars of the realm held him in universal esteem. I myself once served under him and knew him intimately; therefore I venture to record these essentials.

    The Duke of Korea lived seventy-nine years. He passed away at home on the twelfth day of the twelfth month in the year Guiyou of the Yuantong era. In the following year, his widow received the honor of Duchess, and she lived on for six more years until the nineteenth day of the seventh month in the year Jimao of the Zhiyuan era, when she too departed at the age of seventy-four. Seven years after her passing, this shrine was erected, in the third month of the year Yiyou of the Zhizheng era, the fifth of that reign.
